Multi container pods, the sidecar pattern.

In the last notebook we said the pod abstraction earns its keep when you have helper containers. Now we put that to use.

The sidecar pattern is a small companion container that adds a capability to the main container without changing the main container's image. Common examples are a log shipper that tails files the main container writes and forwards them to a central system, a service mesh proxy that intercepts the main container's network traffic, and a config reloader that watches a config map mount and signals the main container when it changes.

What makes the sidecar pattern work is two things, the shared volume and the shared network.

Picture an application container that writes timestamps to a log file, and a second container, the log shipper, that tails that same file. Different containers, but the same file, because the volume is mounted into both. In a real system the shipper would forward those lines to a central logging service.

When a pod has more than one container, you read a specific one's output by passing the container flag to kubectl logs, naming the container you want. Without it, kubectl does not know which container you mean.

And the shared network is easy to prove. If the main container listens on, say, port eighty eighty, the sidecar reaches it simply at localhost, port eighty eighty. No dee-en-ess, no eye-pee lookups, because the two containers share the same network namespace. To put it another way, inside a pod, containers are roommates. They share the address and the cupboards, and they talk to each other just by turning around.
